    pearls: ["The discriminatory zone (hCG 1,500-3,500 mIU/mL) is the KEY clinical decision threshold: empty uterus ABOVE this level is ectopic until proven otherwise; empty uterus BELOW this level is indeterminate and requires serial monitoring -- do NOT treat empirically below the discriminatory zone","A transient hCG rise between days 1 and 4 after methotrexate is EXPECTED and does NOT indicate treatment failure; the critical measurement is the ≥15% decline between days 4 and 7 -- intervening only on days 1-4 may lead to unnecessary surgical intervention","The 53% hCG rise in 48 hours is the minimum expected for viable IUP; however, 15% of normal IUPs show subnormal rise patterns -- never administer methotrexate based solely on a slow rise without TVUS confirmation that there is no viable IUP","Heterotopic pregnancy (simultaneous IUP + ectopic) occurs in approximately 1/30,000 natural conceptions but 1/100 IVF pregnancies -- ALWAYS visualize the adnexa even when an IUP is confirmed in IVF patients","Separation pain after methotrexate (60-75% of patients, days 2-7) must be distinguished from tubal rupture: separation pain is mild-moderate, intermittent, without hemodynamic changes; rupture pain is sudden, severe, and accompanied by tachycardia, hypotension, or peritoneal signs","After salpingostomy (tube-conserving surgery), persistent trophoblast occurs in 5-20% of cases, detected by failure of hCG to decline to zero; methotrexate is typically administered as adjunctive therapy -- weekly hCG monitoring until undetectable is mandatory","Contraception after methotrexate: reliable contraception is required for at least 3 months (one ovulatory cycle after hCG resolution) because methotrexate is teratogenic; folate stores must be replenished before subsequent pregnancy"],
